data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14, new **span conversion rules** cause `array.Contains(num)` to bind to `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Since expression trees cannot represent `Span<T>`/`ReadOnlySpan<T>` parameters, this throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Force the call to bind to the `IEnumerable<T>` overload. Pick any of these:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast the array to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

The same issue affects `Enumerable.Reverse` on arrays (now resolves to the in-place `Span` version). The fix pattern is the same — disambiguate with a cast, `.AsEnumerable()`, or an explicit static call.
